The paper deals with speech separation, which is a subfield of signal processing and machine learning. The most likely category is cs.SD (Sound), which deals with audio and speech processing. The paper also discusses loss functions and their relationship to performance, which falls under cs.SI (Statistical Learning). The use of permutation invariant training (PIT) and neural networks suggests a connection to cs.CL (Computation and Language). The paper also discusses the compatibility of frequency domain processing with classic signal processing tools, which could fall under cs.LG (Machine Learning). Finally, the paper critically assesses the generalization of gains in a more realistic environment, which could fall under cs.SDRL (Sound and Music Computing).
